english:
  title: Epitaph for Lord Choe of Gwangyang, Duke of Great Brilliance and Exemplary Virtue
  author: Lee Jehe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The house of Choe of Wansan rose to renown when its ancestor, Vice Director of the Ministry of Rites, met an honorable death resisting the rebels. Through generations of service, the line produced counselors and ministers.

    Our subject, born of a line so distinguished, received the name Seongjji, with courtesy name Sunbu and sobriquet Songpa. Before his twentieth year, he passed the civil examinations and entered service as an official recorder. Rising through merit and steadfast principle, he advanced to positions of great responsibility—never swayed by fortune or fear, for as he once declared: "Rise and fall rest with Heaven. To tremble before gain is no mark of a true gentleman."

    In the troubled times of the Yuan court, when hidden forces schemed and factions clashed, he stood resolute. When all around him sought advantage through compromise, he alone refused to lend his seal to dangerous documents. "I have held the rank of Prime Minister," he thundered, "and will not be coerced by lesser men." His integrity silenced the conspirators.

    Honored with the title "Duke of Unwavering Virtue and Brilliant Counsel," enfeoffed as Lord of Gwangyang, he spent his final years in quiet refinement—composing verse of grace and depth, discoursing on lofty matters with select friends, asking nothing of the turbulent world. When at last he departed this life at sixty-five, the state itself marked his passing with honor.

    A man born of noble lineage, who found worthy patrons for his gifts, who advanced through propriety and withdrew through righteousness—such rare spirits find support in devoted wives and filial sons. In this present age, one searches in vain for even one in ten possessing such blessings.

    O Lord of Gwangyang, your course was complete. No regret remains.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The position of 'Vice Director of the Ministry of Rites' (禮部郞中) was a significant bureaucratic rank in the Yuan administrative system, reflecting the family's long standing in official service.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to the establishment of a provincial administration (省) reflects the historical tension between Korean autonomy and Yuan imperial authority during this period.
